# Synthetic SGJP-shaped fixture for scripts/compile-sgjp.mjs (FLEKSJA-IMPL-
# PLAN.md SS8, FL-1a row: "fixture ... syntetyczny w formacie z dokumentacji").
# Every line below is hand-typed by the author for this test suite only —
# zero content copied from any real SGJP/PoliMorf/Morfeusz distribution, so
# no licensing question attaches to this file (mirrors the existing
# disclaimer on src/verifier/morph/fixtures/mini-lexicon.js). The real
# artifact (FL-1b, full SGJP compile from the licensed sgjp-*.tab.gz dump)
# is out of scope here and is never produced or imported by this fixture.
#
# Column shape (tab-separated): forma  lemat  tag  klasyfikacja  [kwalifikatory]
# — this is the 5-column source format Morfeusz2.pdf §7.1 "Słownik główny"
# defines verbatim (col 4 = "klasyfikacja nazw własnych", a SEPARATE column,
# not part of the tag; col 5 = pipe-separated qualifiers, optional). The
# colon-segmented positional tag grammar (case/number/gender tokens scanned by
# position-independent membership, not fixed offsets) is Morfeusz2.pdf §1.1.
# Format verified via web research on branch feature/sgjp-format-verify (see
# docs/sgjp-compile.md §"Format zweryfikowany u źródła"); no real SGJP dump
# was downloaded. Classification labels confirmed at source: imię, nazwisko,
# pospolita, geograficzna.
# Twelve lexemes, one row per attested (lemma, case) surface form:
#   Wesołowski (m, adjectival-ski-m), Kania (f, noun-feminine-a) — regular
#     surnames, fully rule-predictable: the compiler must SUBTRACT these
#     (zero footprint in morph-pl.json, paradigms.js reproduces them at
#     runtime). Kania's row set deliberately OMITS the vocative (W): the
#     rule engine's own nounFeminineA generator returns W:null (an explicit,
#     permanent gap — "vocative of feminine surnames left open, practice
#     wavers between -o and the nominative", paradigms.js) — attesting any
#     W form for Kania would necessarily "diverge" against that null and
#     defeat the subtraction this lexeme exists to demonstrate.
#     NOTE (compiler-adjacent finding, out of scope to fix here): an
#     adjectival -ska/-cka/-dzka feminine surname (e.g. "Zawadzka") was
#     deliberately NOT used for this slot — analyzing such a surname BARE
#     (no dictionary hit, i.e. exactly the subtracted/common case) resolves
#     to a WRONG lemma in src/verifier/morph/analyze.js's
#     resolveSurnameWord: surnameLemmaCandidates('Zawadzka') returns the
#     correct self-candidate PLUS spurious cross-lemma collisions
#     ("Zawadzk"/m/noun-masculine, "Zawadzek"/m/noun-masculine-ek, both
#     self-validating because their OWN genitive happens to equal the
#     input "Zawadzka"); analyze.js's "genuine" filter (comment: "must
#     never shadow a candidate that required a REAL inversion") discards
#     ONLY the correct self-matching candidate and keeps a spurious one,
#     so generation silently returns "Zawadzk" instead of "Zawadzkiej".
#     Confirmed pre-existing and independent of this fixture/compiler
#     (reproduces with morph:null, zero compiled data involved) — see the
#     task report for the full trace; not touched by this branch.
#   Kozioł (m)   — genuine dictionary exception with variant forms (two
#     accepted surface forms per oblique case) — must survive subtraction.
#   Fischer (m)  — foreign-orthography surname (isForeignName true, rule
#     engine refuses by construction) — must survive subtraction via the
#     SAME whole-lexeme mechanism, no special-casing.
#   Tomasz (m), Ewa (f) — ordinary given names, full singular paradigm.
#   Maria        — given name with an extra differently-gendered row
#     (nominative only) to exercise multi-gender detection ("m/f"); a
#     plausible stand-in for the real phenomenon, NOT a literal claim about
#     how the real SGJP dump tags this specific name (see docs/sgjp-compile.md).
#   Marek (m)    — given name attested with a SINGLE case only (nominative),
#     proving the compiler never fabricates the missing six forms.
#   powód, pozwany — procedural role nouns/adjectives (classification
#     "pospolita", matched by lemma against src/verifier/case-detector/
#     role-lemmas.js, NOT by name-classification label).
#   sąd          — an ordinary common noun, "pospolita" and NOT a role
#     lemma, with an attached qualifier ("prawn.") on its one row: proves
#     (a) non-role "pospolita" rows are correctly skipped, (b) the optional
#     5th (qualifiers) column parses without breaking the 4-column rows
#     everywhere else in this file.
#   Sopot        — a geographic proper name (classification "geograficzna", a
#     confirmed real SGJP label, Morfeusz2.pdf §7.1): proves a proper-name row
#     whose subclass is NEITHER imię NOR nazwisko is correctly ignored — it
#     falls through every name/role branch and is only tallied in the report.
Wesołowski	Wesołowski	adj:sg:nom:m1:pos	nazwisko
Wesołowskiego	Wesołowski	adj:sg:gen:m1:pos	nazwisko
Wesołowskiemu	Wesołowski	adj:sg:dat:m1:pos	nazwisko
Wesołowskiego	Wesołowski	adj:sg:acc:m1:pos	nazwisko
